03900nam a22005655i 9780520964204DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209642047 a10.1525/97805209642042doi  a(DE-B1597)520817  a(OCoLC)932625504  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL1140002bisacsh1 aSmith, Kyle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstantine and the Captive Christians of Persia :bMartyrdom and Religious Identity in Late Antiquity /cKyle Smith. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage ;v5700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Constantine and the Writing of Fourth-Century History -- tPart One. The Roman Frontier and the Persian War -- tPart Two. Roman Captives and Persian Envoys -- tAppendix A. Constantine's Letter to Shapur: Eusebius's Life of Constantine IV.8-14 -- tAppendix B. Martyrdom of the Captives of Beth Zabdai -- tAppendix C. Martyrdom of Abbot Barshebya, Ten Fellow Brothers, and One Magus -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is widely believed that the Emperor Constantine's conversion to Christianity politicized religious allegiances, dividing the Christian Roman Empire from the Zoroastrian Sasanian Empire and leading to the persecution of Christians in Persia. This account, however, is based on Greek ecclesiastical histories and Syriac martyrdom narratives that date to centuries after the fact. In this groundbreaking study, Kyle Smith analyzes diverse Greek, Latin, and Syriac sources to show that there was not a single history of fourth-century Mesopotamia. By examining the conflicting hagiographical and historical evidence, Constantine and the Captive Christians of Persia presents an evocative and evolving portrait of the first Christian emperor, uncovering how Syriac Christians manipulated the image of their western Christian counterparts to fashion their own political and religious identities during this century of radical change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aSyriac ChristianszIranxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSyriac ChristianszIraqxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520964204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520964204.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles